messages.content: As an AI assistant, my role is to meticulously analyze criminal justice documents and extract information about law enforcement personnel. The response will contain: 1) The name of a law enforcement personnel. The individual's name must be prefixed with one of the following titles to be in law enforcement: Detective, Sergeant, Lieutenant, Captain, Deputy, Officer, Patrol Officer, Criminalist, Technician, Coroner, or Dr. Please prefix the name with 'Officer Name: '. I will derive this data from the following paragraph: At about 12:31am, Investigator Lewis, with the assistance of Chauffer Rodney Robinson rolled the decedent over and placed her in a body bag. When the decedent was moved, investigators observed a single spent casing in the pool of blood where the decedent had been laying. Technician Muhammad photographed and collected the spent casing, which was identified as a

9mm Luger at 12:31am. Sergeant McMullen advised Detective Morton there was a blood trail from the interior hallway were the victim is located to North Derbignay Street. Detective Morton observed the H-10983-09 PAGE 16 At that point the witness observed her sister unresponsive and bleeding on the floor at the entrance to the bedroom. Gordon stated he would kill the witness if the police arrived while he was inside the residence. Both perpetrators then exited the residence with n money, or car keys. The witness notified then police. At 2:30AM Crime Lab Technician Tamika Rogers, Unit 5137, conducted gunshot residue test on both Darceleen Commodore and Earlitta Taylor at the Homicide Office. Coroner's Office Day Records from Detective David Trehan. The documents officially classified the shooting deaths of Patrice Commodore and Jessie Bibbins as a Homicides. At 9:00AM Detective Morton met with witness, Darceleen Commodore at her residence regarding her encounter with Reynell Payne. Commodore advised the Detective that Reynell Payne pressured her to say her son wasn't one of the perpetrators and the older gentleman was the perpetrator. Commodore states the statement given to 1815 Carondelet Street, was developed as a suspect. Homicide Investigators interviewed two eyewitnesses at the Homicide Office. Darceleen Commodore advised Detective Morton she observed the suspect's faces and knew one of the subjects from the neighborhood. Witness Earlita Taylor stated she did not see the perpetrator's faces. Via photographic line-up Darceleen Commodore positively identified Kendall Gordon as one of the two subjects, who entered her home at gunpoint. Commodore was 90% sure. At around 1:00am, Detective Aucoin located a set of keys, which were hanging from a key box in the living room of the residence. Detective Aucoin checked the keys and was successful in locating a key to the front door of the residence. Detective Aucoin, believing that he had exhausted the scene for night, locked and secured the residence and placed a seal from the Orleans Parish Coroner's Office on the door. Detective Aucoin then spoke to two black females who identified themselves as family members of Patrice Commodore, Marie Commodore and Indel Commodore.
